```suggestion
Authors: Artur Szafarczyk, Suraj Krishna M S, Jean-Baptiste Stiegler, Isabelle Dubois,
```

```suggestion
/-- We define `preCantorSet n` as ... -/
def preCantorSet : ℕ → Set ℝ
```
You can give any description here, maybe just add a reference to wikipedia above and refer to that.

Maybe something like
```suggestion
/-- The pre-Cantor set of order `n` is defined inductively by starting from `[0, 1]` and successively
removing the middle thirds. -/
def preCantorSet : ℕ → Set ℝ
```
It doesn't seem like these comments were ever addressed.
You can start working in the namespace `cantorSet`, or something like that, so all the names will start with it.
Can you please split this in two theorems? (if you are not sure about the name just try a simple guess)
The fact of the matter is that this can't really be split because the proof goes inductively to show that 1/4 is in ``preCantorSet n`` we need that 3/4 is in `preCantorSet (n-1)`` and vice versa.
What is `preCantorSet 0`, it is the whole interval? In that case you can just add a `simp` lemma that describe it.

I'm sorry but I don't understand. ``preCantorSet 0`` is defined as ``Set.Icc 0 1``. What is the lemma that you think should be added? Something like "for every x in preCantorSet 0, x is greater than 0 and smaller than 1"? That's what's needed here.

No no, I literally mean this lemma, the proof will indeed be `rfl`, since as you say it is true by definition. There are several reason to do that, for example tagging it `simp` will make possible to prove stuff like `0 ∈ preCantorSet 0` simply writing `simp` (now you have to write `simp [preCantorSet]`, that is not very longer, but things can be more complicated).
Same for `preCantorSet n.succ`: we can have a `simp` lemma (whose proof is `rfl`) that describe it using the union. In this way `simp` becames more powerful and it can help more.
My confusion is the same as above, what lemma do you think is missing? ``preCantorSet (n+1)`` is already described as a union of two sets.

```suggestion
theorem zero_mem_cantorSet : 0 ∈ cantorSet := by
  simp only [cantorSet, iInf, Set.sInf_eq_sInter, Set.sInter_range, Set.mem_iInter]
  exact zero_mem_preCantorSet
```
```suggestion
theorem zero_mem_cantorSet : 0 ∈ cantorSet := by simp [cantorSet, zero_mem_preCantorSet]
```
untested.
This should be an instance.
Uh, really?
`IsClosed` is a class, so I guess this can work. But you're right that most of the time we don't do that.
Unless there is a later need for `IsClosed cantorSet` to be found by typeclass search, I want to say this can stay a lemma

You don't need to write this instance explicitly.
```suggestion
```
It is already automatically inferred as you can check by doing
```
instance cantorSet.metricSpace : MetricSpace cantorSet := inferInstance
```
or
```
#synth MetricSpace cantorSet
```

```suggestion
def cantorSet := iInter preCantorSet
```
or, more readably,
```suggestion
def cantorSet : ℝ := ⋂ n, preCantorSet n
```

```suggestion
/-- The Cantor set is the intersection of all pre-Cantor sets. -/
```

More idiomatically,
```suggestion
  | n + 1 => (· / 3) '' preCantorSet n ∪ (fun x ↦ (2 + x) / 3) '' preCantorSet n
```

As Riccardo indicated, the following two theorems will make your life easier:
```suggestion

@[simp] lemma preCantorSet_zero : preCantorSet 0 = Set.Icc 0 1 := rfl
@[simp] lemma preCantorSet_succ (n : ℕ) :
    preCantorSet (n + 1) = (· / 3) '' preCantorSet n ∪ (fun x ↦ (2 + x) / 3) '' preCantorSet n :=
  rfl
```
Thank you, I finally understand. Very interesting that this actually helps with anything.

If you want something to look up, those are called "equational lemmas". Lean in fact knows how to generate them, and this is what `simp` rewrites with when you write `simp [preCantorSet]` (in particular, it does *not* just unfold the definition of `preCantorSet`), however it is good practice to write them yourself as
1. Lean is kind of inconsistent as to how those equational lemmas should look like, eg in a recent Lean 4 version there would be a single equational lemma of the form `preCantorSet n = match n with | 0 => Set.Icc 0 1 | n + 1 => ...` instead of the pair `preCantorSet_zero`, `preCantorSet_succ` that I wrote about
2. If your definition ever changes, the autogenerated equational lemmas will too, which is undesirable from an API stability perspective
understood, thanks!

```suggestion
# Ternary Cantor Set

This file defines the Cantor ternary set and proves a few properties.

## Main Definitions

* `preCantorSet n`: The order `n` pre-Cantor set, defined inductively.
* `cantorSet`: The ternary Cantor set, defined as the intersection of all
  pre-Cantor sets.
```

Several minor points:
1. the correct tactic to use here is `norm_num`, not `linarith`, despite the fact that the latter works.
2. style nit: we don't insert blank lines into proofs
3. I don't think the comments are really necessary, but if you want to keep them that's fine. However, they're not quite correct as stated.
4. another style nit: we try to put spaces around binary operations, so `1 / 4` instead of `1/4`.
```suggestion
    simp only [preCantorSet_zero, inv_nonneg]
    refine ⟨⟨ ?_, ?_⟩, ?_, ?_⟩ <;> norm_num
  | succ n ih =>
    apply And.intro
    · -- goal: 1 / 4 ∈ preCantorSet (n + 1)
      -- follows by the inductive hyphothesis, since 3 / 4 ∈ preCantorSet n
      exact Or.inl ⟨3 / 4, ih.2, by norm_num⟩
    · -- goal: 3 / 4 ∈ preCantorSet (n + 1)
      -- follows by the inductive hyphothesis, since 1 / 4 ∈ preCantorSet n
      exact Or.inr ⟨1 / 4, ih.1, by norm_num⟩
```

We have a lemma for this :smile:
```suggestion
lemma cantorSet_subset_unitInterval : cantorSet ⊆ Set.Icc 0 1 :=
  Set.iInter_subset _ 0
```

We have a lemma for this too.
```suggestion
theorem quarter_mem_cantorSet : 1/4 ∈ cantorSet :=
  Set.mem_iInter.mpr quarter_mem_preCantorSet
```

it's generally undesirable to name goals with inscrutable names like `?succ.refine_1.hf`, and in this case, there's a simpler approach. Note that you can use dot notation to go directly from the homeomorphisms to closed embeddings.
```suggestion
    · simpa [f, div_eq_inv_mul] using f.closedEmbedding.closed_iff_image_closed.mp ih
    · simpa [g, f, div_eq_inv_mul] using g.closedEmbedding.closed_iff_image_closed.mp ih
```

  let g := (Homeomorph.addLeft (2 : ℝ)).trans f
```

You might want this for `preCantor` sets at some point. Maybe factor that out as a lemma?
Good idea! I did that.

I don't think `preCantorSet` is standard terminology, nor "order `n`", so maybe specify what you mean here. Maybe something like:

* `preCantorSet n`: The order `n` pre-Cantor set, defined inductively as the union of the images under the functions `(· ‌/ 3)` and `(2 * · / 3)`, with `preCantorSet 0 := Set.Icc 0 1`
```

Could you copy the doc-string from above here, otherwise the hover-over is annoying.
You mean writing the definition of ``preCantorSet`` here again, i.e. having the same thing twice?

Yes, this (modulo linebreak):
```suggestion
/-- The order `n` pre-Cantor set, defined inductively as the union of the images under the functions `(· / 3)` and `(2 * · / 3)`, with `preCantorSet 0 := Set.Icc 0 1`, i.e. `preCantorSet 0` is the unit interval [0,1]. -/
```

Edit: or what Yael suggested: https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/pull/11761#discussion_r1545265247

@jaklt yes, it needs to be duplicated. The first one is for the website documentation so that someone reading only the top can comprehend what's going on. 

The do string on the `def` itself also goes on the website (so the info is duplicates there), but crucially, this docstring is also displayed when you hover over `preCantorSet` in VS Code, even in a different file. This is why it's important.
Also this could be more informative: The Cantor sets is the subset of the unit interval created by iteratively removing the open middle third of each interval. Or something along those lines.
This is now addressed.

```suggestion

    union of the images under the functions `(· / 3)` and `(2 * · / 3)` of `preCantorSet n`.
```
Am I confused or do the second functions not match up?
Yes, you're quite right.
